  "text": "C and PrP Sc , PrP*, may also be plausible. Although proteinase resistant PrP Sc is not always found an intermediate non-proteinase K resistant PrP, may also act as a toxic molecule. Biochemical differences exist between PrP C and PrP Sc and include detergent insolubility and proteinase K resistance [CITATION_1] . But more importantly for a gain of abnormal function is that the isoforms differ in metal binding properties [CITATION_2] , additionally, apo-PrP C and PrP Sc , unlike metal bound PrP C , can bind plasminogen and can stimulate the generation of plasmin [CITATION_3] . As the function of PrP C would appear important in the understanding of TSEs, and different regions of PrP C elicit different functions or trafficking for the protein in the cell, the structure function relationship will be discussed here.",
